				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">thefox wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Grapeshot wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Here's a project from last year that turns on the motor when both the strobe and clock lines are held high.</div>The problem with this method is that on NES the clock line can't be held high, it'll only go high momentarily when $4016/$4017 is read. So this method would need a quite lot of CPU time.</div> Hm. That could be fixed in analog (to charge a capacitor with an assymetric charge/discharge path), but we should probably just use a microcontroller instead now.
<br />
<br />*EDIT: No, wait, better idea! Instead of the AND gate, use a latch or shift register, clocked on RD  but with Din hooked up to the strobe line from the NES. Then, after both joypads have been read, reassert strobe and read once from each joypad you want to vibrate.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

